## What is String

A String in Java is a sequence of characters.

Example:
"Hello"
"Java"
"Programming"

---

## Two Ways to Create String

1. String Literal
2. Using new Keyword

---

## 1. String Literal

String created using double quotes.

Example:

String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello";

Here Java uses **String Constant Pool**.

Both s1 and s2 refer to the **same memory location**.

Example program:

public class Test {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String s1 = "Java";
        String s2 = "Java";

        System.out.println(s1 == s2);

    }

}

Output

true

---

## 2. String Using new Keyword

String object created using **new keyword**.

Example:

String s1 = new String("Java");
String s2 = new String("Java");

Here two different objects are created in **heap memory**.

Example program:

public class Test {

    public static void main(String[] args) {

        String s1 = new String("Java");
        String s2 = new String("Java");

        System.out.println(s1 == s2);

    }

}

Output

false

---

## Key Difference

String Literal

- Stored in String Pool
- Memory efficient
- Same object reused

String using new

- Stored in Heap Memory
- New object created every time

- Difference between both
